queryLines:
with workspaces as (
     select workspace_id,
            workspace_name,
            workspace_url
       from system.access.workspaces_latest
), warehouse_scd as (
     select wh.*,
            w.workspace_name,
            w.workspace_url,
            wh.change_time as valid_from,
            lead(wh.change_time) over (
                partition by wh.workspace_id, wh.warehouse_id
                order by wh.change_time
            ) as valid_to,
            case
                when row_number() over (partition by wh.workspace_id, wh.warehouse_id order by wh.change_time) = 1 then 'add'
                when lead(wh.change_time) over (partition by wh.workspace_id, wh.warehouse_id order by wh.change_time) is null then 'delete'
                else 'update'
            end as change_op
       from system.compute.warehouses wh
       left join workspaces w
         on w.workspace_id = wh.workspace_id
), query_history as (
     select q.query_source.dashboard_id as dashboard_id,
            q.*,
            wh.warehouse_name || ' (' || wh.warehouse_id || ')' as warehouse,
            wh.workspace_name,
            wh.workspace_url,
            wh.workspace_url || '/dashboardsv3/' || q.query_source.dashboard_id || '/published' as dashboard_url,
            wh.workspace_url || '/sql/history?queryId=' || q.statement_id as statement_url,
            wh.workspace_url || '/sql/warehouses/' || wh.warehouse_id || '/monitoring' as warehouse_url,
            total_duration_ms / 1000    as total_duration_sec
       from system.query.history q
       left join warehouse_scd wh
         on q.compute.warehouse_id = wh.warehouse_id
        and q.start_time between wh.valid_from and coalesce(wh.valid_to, current_timestamp())
      where q.compute.warehouse_id is not null
        and q.query_source.dashboard_id is not null
        and start_time between cast(:time_range.min as timestamp) AND cast(:time_range.max as timestamp)
)
select *
  from query_history
 where dashboard_id = :dashboard_id
   and total_duration_sec > :min_total_duration_sec

datasets.name: 273f7b81
queryLines:
with workspaces as (
     select workspace_id,
            workspace_name,
            workspace_url
       from system.access.workspaces_latest
), warehouse_scd as (
     select wh.*,
            w.workspace_name,
            w.workspace_url,
            wh.change_time as valid_from,
            lead(wh.change_time) over (
                partition by wh.workspace_id, wh.warehouse_id
                order by wh.change_time
            ) as valid_to,
            case
                when row_number() over (partition by wh.workspace_id, wh.warehouse_id order by wh.change_time) = 1 then 'add'
                when lead(wh.change_time) over (partition by wh.workspace_id, wh.warehouse_id order by wh.change_time) is null then 'delete'
                else 'update'
            end as change_op
       from system.compute.warehouses wh
       left join workspaces w
         on w.workspace_id = wh.workspace_id
), query_history as (
     select date(q.start_time)          as start_date,
            q.statement_text            as statement_text,
            q.statement_id              as statement_id,
            q.query_source.dashboard_id as dashboard_id,
            wh.workspace_url || '/dashboardsv3/' || q.query_source.dashboard_id || '/published' as dashboard_url,
            total_duration_ms / 1000    as total_duration_sec,
            q.client_application        as client_application,
            q.produced_rows             as produced_rows,
            q.from_result_cache         as from_result_cache,
            wh.workspace_url || '/sql/history?queryId=' || q.statement_id as statement_url,
            q.read_bytes / 1024 / 1024 / 1024 as read_gb,
            q.written_bytes / 1024 / 1024 / 1024 as written_gb
       from system.query.history q
       left join warehouse_scd wh
         on q.compute.warehouse_id = wh.warehouse_id
        and q.start_time between wh.valid_from and coalesce(wh.valid_to, current_timestamp())
      where q.compute.warehouse_id is not null
        and q.query_source.dashboard_id is not null
        and start_time between cast(:time_range.min as timestamp) AND cast(:time_range.max as timestamp)
)
select statement_text,
       dashboard_id,
       dashboard_url,
       avg(total_duration_sec)                  as avg_duration_sec,
       min(read_gb)                             as min_read_gb,
       max(read_gb)                             as max_read_gb,
       avg(read_gb)                             as avg_read_gb,
       count(1)                                 as query_count,
       slice(collect_set(statement_id), 1, 20)  as statements
  from query_history
 where client_application = 'Databricks SQL Dashboard'
   and produced_rows >= :produced_rows_min
   and (produced_rows <= :produced_rows_max or :produced_rows_max = 'All')
   and array_contains(:from_result_cache, cast(from_result_cache as string))
   and total_duration_sec > :min_total_duration_sec
   and read_gb > :min_read_gb
 group by all
 order by query_count desc,
          avg_duration_sec desc

## Query analysis

Looking for problematic dashboards for longer-running, repeated queries that read a lot of data.

With the default filters, we identify any dashboards that contain queries consuming more than 1 GB of data and running for over 10 minutes. Doing this repeatedly is something that should be optimised.

## Query Cache misses

We want to identify all dashboards that run queries producing fewer than 100,000 rows but also fail to utilise the query cache. Refer to the [Databricks docs](https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/sql/user/queries/query-caching) for details on DBSQL caching. With the default filter we only look at queries that run for more than 10 mins but it can be useful to look at shorter queries if there is a high repeat count.

This is often due to the fact that the underlying dataset is changing, necessitating the need to rerun the query. A classic example of this would be direct queries on the [system tables](https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/admin/system-tables/). These might be candidates for materialisation.

To drill down to statement-level detail right click on a bar and select:

```py
